(261, 0, '_transient_rss_0e98340d518ceed28b29f102e202ba76', 'O:9:"MagpieRSS":19:{s:6:"parser";i:0;s:12:"current_item";a:0:{}s:5:"items";a:10:{i:0;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:61:"The new ‘Newsletter Sign-up’ plugin – are you using it?";s:4:"link";s:61:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~3/3_MepmlvtWs/";s:8:"comments";s:82:"http://dannyvankooten.com/359/newsletter-sign-up-plugin-are-you-using-it/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Sat, 26 Mar 2011 18:42:59 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:16:"Danny van Kooten";}s:8:"category";s:78:"Affiliate MarketingUsabilityWordPressmailinglistnewsletterPluginssubscribersWP";s:4:"guid";s:32:"http://dannyvankooten.com/?p=359";s:11:"description";s:649:"<p>Last week i&#8217;ve released a new and improved version of &#8216;Qoate Newsletter Sign-up&#8217;, one of my older plugins for WordPress that adds a &#8216;Sign me up for your newsletter&#8217; checkbox to your comment form. This makes it easy for your commenters to sign-up for your mailinglist and thus turn them into subscribers. If you were<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/359/newsletter-sign-up-plugin-are-you-using-it/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/359/newsletter-sign-up-plugin-are-you-using-it/">The new &#8216;Newsletter Sign-up&#8217; plugin &#8211; are you using it?</a></p>";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:3641:"<p>Last week i&#8217;ve released a new and improved version of &#8216;Qoate Newsletter Sign-up&#8217;, one of my older plugins for WordPress that adds a &#8216;Sign me up for your newsletter&#8217; checkbox to your comment form. This makes it easy for your commenters to sign-up for your mailinglist and thus turn them into subscribers.</p><p>If you were previously using the &#8216;old&#8217; plugin (Qoate Newsletter Sign-up) it is highly recommended that you start using <a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/newsletter-sign-up/">Newsletter Sign-up</a> right away. I recoded the whole thing from scratch resulting in much cleaner code, higher compatibility and probably the most important thing, better performance.</p><p>Not using the plugin yet? Care to read on why you should start using it?</p><h3>What does this &#8216;Newsletter Sign-up&#8217; plugin do exactly?</h3><p>The plugin gives you the possibility to add a checkbox to your comment forms and your registration forms. Users who take the effort to comment on your posts are most likely dedicated readers of your blog and most likely they&#8217;d like to subscribe to your newsletter too. With this plugin enabled all they have to do is tick a checkbox and voila, they&#8217;re subscribed.</p><h4>Behind the scenes and the CAN-SPAM act</h4><p>As soon as this plugin detects that someone ticked the checkbox upon posting their comment it mimics the normal POST request that a user would do when subscribing to your newsletter trough a normal sign-up form. In most cases the subscriber will then receive a confirmation e-mail to make sure that they are willingly signing-up to your newsletter. This depends on your newsletter service and settings tho. This plugin is <strong>not</strong> silently subscribing your commenters, and thus not violating the CAN-SPAM act.</p><h3>I want to boost my newsletter subscribers, how easy is this plugin to set-up?</h3><p>I&#8217;ve made it as easy as possible. Pictures tell more then a thousand words so let me show you how this plugin will look in your WordPress backend.</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/newsletter-sign-up-backend.jpg"><img src="http://dannyvankooten.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/newsletter-sign-up-backend.jpg" alt="" title="Backend of Newsletter Sign-up plugin." width="485" height="522" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-362" /></a></p><p>As you can see you have the option to select one of the major newsletter services from a select list. This will help you by filling in some of the values that are used for everyone using that newsletter service. Then all that&#8217;s left for you is to select some information that is specific to your list. You can find all this information in a sign-up form that you would normally embed on your website. For more information on how to find this values take a look at &#8220;<a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/wordpress-plugins/newsletter-sign-up/">Configuring Newsletter Sign-up</a>&#8220;.</p><p>If you&#8217;re not already using Newsletter Sign-up you should definetly give it a try and see what it does to your mailinglist. I hereby dare you to post some results after a few weeks of using this plugin.</p><p><a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/newsletter-sign-up/"><strong>Download Newsletter Sign-up from the WordPress repository now!</strong></a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/359/newsletter-sign-up-plugin-are-you-using-it/">The new &#8216;Newsletter Sign-up&#8217; plugin &#8211; are you using it?</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/3_MepmlvtWs" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:78:"http://dannyvankooten.com/359/newsletter-sign-up-plugin-are-you-using-it/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:2:"35";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:73:"http://dannyvankooten.com/359/newsletter-sign-up-plugin-are-you-using-it/";}s:7:"summary";s:649:"<p>Last week i&#8217;ve released a new and improved version of &#8216;Qoate Newsletter Sign-up&#8217;, one of my older plugins for WordPress that adds a &#8216;Sign me up for your newsletter&#8217; checkbox to your comment form. This makes it easy for your commenters to sign-up for your mailinglist and thus turn them into subscribers. If you were<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/359/newsletter-sign-up-plugin-are-you-using-it/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/359/newsletter-sign-up-plugin-are-you-using-it/">The new &#8216;Newsletter Sign-up&#8217; plugin &#8211; are you using it?</a></p>";s:12:"atom_content";s:3641:"<p>Last week i&#8217;ve released a new and improved version of &#8216;Qoate Newsletter Sign-up&#8217;, one of my older plugins for WordPress that adds a &#8216;Sign me up for your newsletter&#8217; checkbox to your comment form. This makes it easy for your commenters to sign-up for your mailinglist and thus turn them into subscribers.</p><p>If you were previously using the &#8216;old&#8217; plugin (Qoate Newsletter Sign-up) it is highly recommended that you start using <a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/newsletter-sign-up/">Newsletter Sign-up</a> right away. I recoded the whole thing from scratch resulting in much cleaner code, higher compatibility and probably the most important thing, better performance.</p><p>Not using the plugin yet? Care to read on why you should start using it?</p><h3>What does this &#8216;Newsletter Sign-up&#8217; plugin do exactly?</h3><p>The plugin gives you the possibility to add a checkbox to your comment forms and your registration forms. Users who take the effort to comment on your posts are most likely dedicated readers of your blog and most likely they&#8217;d like to subscribe to your newsletter too. With this plugin enabled all they have to do is tick a checkbox and voila, they&#8217;re subscribed.</p><h4>Behind the scenes and the CAN-SPAM act</h4><p>As soon as this plugin detects that someone ticked the checkbox upon posting their comment it mimics the normal POST request that a user would do when subscribing to your newsletter trough a normal sign-up form. In most cases the subscriber will then receive a confirmation e-mail to make sure that they are willingly signing-up to your newsletter. This depends on your newsletter service and settings tho. This plugin is <strong>not</strong> silently subscribing your commenters, and thus not violating the CAN-SPAM act.</p><h3>I want to boost my newsletter subscribers, how easy is this plugin to set-up?</h3><p>I&#8217;ve made it as easy as possible. Pictures tell more then a thousand words so let me show you how this plugin will look in your WordPress backend.</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/newsletter-sign-up-backend.jpg"><img src="http://dannyvankooten.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/newsletter-sign-up-backend.jpg" alt="" title="Backend of Newsletter Sign-up plugin." width="485" height="522" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-362" /></a></p><p>As you can see you have the option to select one of the major newsletter services from a select list. This will help you by filling in some of the values that are used for everyone using that newsletter service. Then all that&#8217;s left for you is to select some information that is specific to your list. You can find all this information in a sign-up form that you would normally embed on your website. For more information on how to find this values take a look at &#8220;<a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/wordpress-plugins/newsletter-sign-up/">Configuring Newsletter Sign-up</a>&#8220;.</p><p>If you&#8217;re not already using Newsletter Sign-up you should definetly give it a try and see what it does to your mailinglist. I hereby dare you to post some results after a few weeks of using this plugin.</p><p><a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/newsletter-sign-up/"><strong>Download Newsletter Sign-up from the WordPress repository now!</strong></a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/359/newsletter-sign-up-plugin-are-you-using-it/">The new &#8216;Newsletter Sign-up&#8217; plugin &#8211; are you using it?</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/3_MepmlvtWs" height="1" width="1"/>";}i:1;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:27:"CodeIgniter Sessions in IE7";s:4:"link";s:61:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~3/LxmgoDq7AvA/";s:8:"comments";s:67:"http://dannyvankooten.com/350/codeigniter-sessions-in-ie7/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Mon, 31 Jan 2011 07:53:31 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:16:"Danny van Kooten";}s:8:"category";s:51:"CodeIgniterBrowser CompatibilitycodeigniterSessions";s:4:"guid";s:32:"http://dannyvankooten.com/?p=350";s:11:"description";s:561:"<p>Yesterday, while working on a fairly simple application that required a login functionality I came across a very strange problem with CodeIgniter and sessions in Internet Explorer 7. While testing everything seemed to work fine in all browsers, even in IE6 (I use IETester to test for the older versions of IE). But&#8230; here comes<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/350/codeigniter-sessions-in-ie7/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/350/codeigniter-sessions-in-ie7/">CodeIgniter Sessions in IE7</a></p>";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:2385:"<p>Yesterday, while working on a fairly simple application that required a login functionality I came across a very strange problem with CodeIgniter and sessions in Internet Explorer 7. While testing everything seemed to work fine in all browsers, even in IE6 (I use IETester to test for the older versions of IE).</p><h3>But&#8230; here comes the problem</h3><p> When showing the application to some friends it turned out that they could not log in. At first I thought maybe their browser (IE 7) was blocking cookies so I asked them to change their security settings from high to normal or normal-high. Apparently that didn&#8217;t do anything.</p><p>After checking my code and some more testing I excluded my code from being the problem. A few google queries later I found out that more CodeIgniter users have been experiencing the same problem with Internet Explorer 7 and CodeIgniter sessions not being stored.</p><h2>IE7 and the CI_Session class</h2><p>Since the CodeIgniter sessions work fine in some IE7 browsers and fail miserably in others there&#8217;s no definite fix for this problem. One thing that might be causing it is the underscore (_) in the cookie name that stores the session variables. The default CI cookie name is &#8216;ci_session&#8217;. Try removing the underscore and see how that works for you (did it for me).</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n$config[''sess_cookie_name'']		= ''cisession''; // note: no more underscore\n</pre><p>When that didn&#8217;t do the trick for you you might try checking you&#8217;re server&#8217;s time settings. When cookies are being stored they are given a lifetime. It could be that you&#8217;re server&#8217;s time is a few hours behind and thus cookies will be removed immediately since their lifetime is already over.</p><p>The last, but best thing you can do is to drop the CodeIgniter session library and start using PHP&#8217;s default session handling using<em> session_start()</em>, <em>$_SESSION[]</em>, <em>unset</em> and <em>session_destroy</em>. Have a look at the <a href="http://codeigniter.com/wiki/Native_session/">CodeIgniter Native Session Library</a> if you really need to use a library to handle your sessions.</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/350/codeigniter-sessions-in-ie7/">CodeIgniter Sessions in IE7</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/LxmgoDq7AvA" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:63:"http://dannyvankooten.com/350/codeigniter-sessions-in-ie7/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:1:"1";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:58:"http://dannyvankooten.com/350/codeigniter-sessions-in-ie7/";}s:7:"summary";s:561:"<p>Yesterday, while working on a fairly simple application that required a login functionality I came across a very strange problem with CodeIgniter and sessions in Internet Explorer 7. While testing everything seemed to work fine in all browsers, even in IE6 (I use IETester to test for the older versions of IE). But&#8230; here comes<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/350/codeigniter-sessions-in-ie7/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/350/codeigniter-sessions-in-ie7/">CodeIgniter Sessions in IE7</a></p>";s:12:"atom_content";s:2385:"<p>Yesterday, while working on a fairly simple application that required a login functionality I came across a very strange problem with CodeIgniter and sessions in Internet Explorer 7. While testing everything seemed to work fine in all browsers, even in IE6 (I use IETester to test for the older versions of IE).</p><h3>But&#8230; here comes the problem</h3><p> When showing the application to some friends it turned out that they could not log in. At first I thought maybe their browser (IE 7) was blocking cookies so I asked them to change their security settings from high to normal or normal-high. Apparently that didn&#8217;t do anything.</p><p>After checking my code and some more testing I excluded my code from being the problem. A few google queries later I found out that more CodeIgniter users have been experiencing the same problem with Internet Explorer 7 and CodeIgniter sessions not being stored.</p><h2>IE7 and the CI_Session class</h2><p>Since the CodeIgniter sessions work fine in some IE7 browsers and fail miserably in others there&#8217;s no definite fix for this problem. One thing that might be causing it is the underscore (_) in the cookie name that stores the session variables. The default CI cookie name is &#8216;ci_session&#8217;. Try removing the underscore and see how that works for you (did it for me).</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n$config[''sess_cookie_name'']		= ''cisession''; // note: no more underscore\n</pre><p>When that didn&#8217;t do the trick for you you might try checking you&#8217;re server&#8217;s time settings. When cookies are being stored they are given a lifetime. It could be that you&#8217;re server&#8217;s time is a few hours behind and thus cookies will be removed immediately since their lifetime is already over.</p><p>The last, but best thing you can do is to drop the CodeIgniter session library and start using PHP&#8217;s default session handling using<em> session_start()</em>, <em>$_SESSION[]</em>, <em>unset</em> and <em>session_destroy</em>. Have a look at the <a href="http://codeigniter.com/wiki/Native_session/">CodeIgniter Native Session Library</a> if you really need to use a library to handle your sessions.</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/350/codeigniter-sessions-in-ie7/">CodeIgniter Sessions in IE7</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/LxmgoDq7AvA" height="1" width="1"/>";}i:2;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:26:"IE fix for HTML 5 elements";s:4:"link";s:61:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~3/Z_JbeTx_q7Y/";s:8:"comments";s:66:"http://dannyvankooten.com/342/ie-fix-for-html-5-elements/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Wed, 29 Dec 2010 19:15:53 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:16:"Danny van Kooten";}s:8:"category";s:36:"HTML 5Browser CompatibilitySemantics";s:4:"guid";s:32:"http://dannyvankooten.com/?p=342";s:11:"description";s:525:"<p>If any of you had a look in the source code of my new theme here on DannyvanKooten.com you might have noticed that i&#8217;ve used some new HTML 5 elements for the mark-up. Nothing fancy, just trying to add some more semantic value to the different parts of a WordPress theme. The sidebar for example<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/342/ie-fix-for-html-5-elements/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/342/ie-fix-for-html-5-elements/">IE fix for HTML 5 elements</a></p>";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:2529:"<p>If any of you had a look in the source code of my new theme here on DannyvanKooten.com you might have noticed that i&#8217;ve used some new HTML 5 elements for the mark-up. Nothing fancy, just trying to add some more semantic value to the different parts of a WordPress theme. The sidebar for example is no longer wrapped in a div element but is now wrapped in an aside element.</p><p>HTML 5 is far from finished (for those of you that want to know how many days are left till the official release date: check out <a href="http://ishtml5readyyet.com/">ishtml5readyyet.com</a>, make sure that you check out the source code of the page too) and not all major (or less major) browsers support the new semantic elements yet. Internet Explorer for example has some problems seeing and thus styling the elements, resulting in a messed up layout. Luckily, there is an easy fix for this.</p><h2>IE fix for HTML 5 elements</h2><p>Because IE 8 and lower does not see the elements it cannot style the elements. Resolving this issue is easy, just create the elements using JavaScript. When you do this before the page is rendered, in the head section of your webpage, IE will have no problem styling our newly created elements. This is called the &#8220;HTML 5 shiv&#8221;</p><p>You can just use the usual JavaScript function createElement() to create the elements you&#8217;ve used, this goes as followed:</p><pre class="qoate-code">\ndocument.createElement("header"); //repeat for all used "new" elements\n</pre><p>That&#8217;s one way to do it. An easier way is to use the HTML 5 shiv that&#8217;s hosted on googlecode by Remy Sharp. I&#8217;m using it myself too. It&#8217;s minified and wrapped in conditional tags so it&#8217;s only a few bytes that have to be downloaded by browsers like IE 8 and below to be able to render the &#8220;new&#8221; elements. Just add the following script tags to your head section and all browsers should be fine rendering the &#8220;new&#8221; HTML 5 elements.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;!--[if IE]&gt;\n	&lt;script src="http://html5shiv.googlecode.com/svn/trunk/html5.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;![endif]--&gt;\n</pre><p>The JS script uses conditionals itself too so if you leave out the if IE conditionals the script will still not be ran by FireFox 3+ or Webkit browsers. Happy HTML 5 theming!</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/342/ie-fix-for-html-5-elements/">IE fix for HTML 5 elements</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/Z_JbeTx_q7Y" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:62:"http://dannyvankooten.com/342/ie-fix-for-html-5-elements/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:1:"3";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:57:"http://dannyvankooten.com/342/ie-fix-for-html-5-elements/";}s:7:"summary";s:525:"<p>If any of you had a look in the source code of my new theme here on DannyvanKooten.com you might have noticed that i&#8217;ve used some new HTML 5 elements for the mark-up. Nothing fancy, just trying to add some more semantic value to the different parts of a WordPress theme. The sidebar for example<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/342/ie-fix-for-html-5-elements/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/342/ie-fix-for-html-5-elements/">IE fix for HTML 5 elements</a></p>";s:12:"atom_content";s:2529:"<p>If any of you had a look in the source code of my new theme here on DannyvanKooten.com you might have noticed that i&#8217;ve used some new HTML 5 elements for the mark-up. Nothing fancy, just trying to add some more semantic value to the different parts of a WordPress theme. The sidebar for example is no longer wrapped in a div element but is now wrapped in an aside element.</p><p>HTML 5 is far from finished (for those of you that want to know how many days are left till the official release date: check out <a href="http://ishtml5readyyet.com/">ishtml5readyyet.com</a>, make sure that you check out the source code of the page too) and not all major (or less major) browsers support the new semantic elements yet. Internet Explorer for example has some problems seeing and thus styling the elements, resulting in a messed up layout. Luckily, there is an easy fix for this.</p><h2>IE fix for HTML 5 elements</h2><p>Because IE 8 and lower does not see the elements it cannot style the elements. Resolving this issue is easy, just create the elements using JavaScript. When you do this before the page is rendered, in the head section of your webpage, IE will have no problem styling our newly created elements. This is called the &#8220;HTML 5 shiv&#8221;</p><p>You can just use the usual JavaScript function createElement() to create the elements you&#8217;ve used, this goes as followed:</p><pre class="qoate-code">\ndocument.createElement("header"); //repeat for all used "new" elements\n</pre><p>That&#8217;s one way to do it. An easier way is to use the HTML 5 shiv that&#8217;s hosted on googlecode by Remy Sharp. I&#8217;m using it myself too. It&#8217;s minified and wrapped in conditional tags so it&#8217;s only a few bytes that have to be downloaded by browsers like IE 8 and below to be able to render the &#8220;new&#8221; elements. Just add the following script tags to your head section and all browsers should be fine rendering the &#8220;new&#8221; HTML 5 elements.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;!--[if IE]&gt;\n	&lt;script src="http://html5shiv.googlecode.com/svn/trunk/html5.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;\n&lt;![endif]--&gt;\n</pre><p>The JS script uses conditionals itself too so if you leave out the if IE conditionals the script will still not be ran by FireFox 3+ or Webkit browsers. Happy HTML 5 theming!</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/342/ie-fix-for-html-5-elements/">IE fix for HTML 5 elements</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/Z_JbeTx_q7Y" height="1" width="1"/>";}i:3;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:42:"Use PHP to create a dynamic CSS stylesheet";s:4:"link";s:61:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~3/OUHeMSNXsKU/";s:8:"comments";s:74:"http://dannyvankooten.com/327/use-php-to-create-a-css-stylesheet/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Mon, 27 Dec 2010 18:20:04 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:16:"Danny van Kooten";}s:8:"category";s:31:"WebdevelopmentWordPressCSSPHPWP";s:4:"guid";s:32:"http://dannyvankooten.com/?p=327";s:11:"description";s:547:"<p>Did you know that you can create a dynamic CSS stylesheet using PHP? I see a lot of themes and plugins for WordPress where users can set simple styling rules like custom colors. Most of the times these style rules just get printed in the head section of the page where they are needed. Now,<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/327/use-php-to-create-a-css-stylesheet/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/327/use-php-to-create-a-css-stylesheet/">Use PHP to create a dynamic CSS stylesheet</a></p>";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:3979:"<p>Did you know that you can create a dynamic CSS stylesheet using PHP? I see a lot of themes and plugins for WordPress where users can set simple styling rules like custom colors. Most of the times these style rules just get printed in the head section of the page where they are needed. Now, this could be done a lot easier using a dynamic stylesheet and efficiently using the browser&#8217;s cache, saving your visitors some precious bytes and thus download time.</p><h2>The correct content-type: &#8220;text/css&#8221;</h2><p>To create a dynamic stylesheet using PHP you can just create a file like &#8220;style.php&#8221;. Now, if you call this file from your pages like you would call a normal stylesheet this won&#8217;t work. We have to tell the browser we are actually dealing with a stylesheet.</p><p>This can easily be done by setting the content-type header by using PHP&#8217;s header function, just add the following piece of code at the top of your newly created style.php file.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;?php header(''Content-type: text/css''); ?&gt;\n</pre><p>Now the browser nows that the rest of this file should be handled like it actually is a CSS file.</p><h2>Passing our dynamic variables</h2><p>Now, to use some dynamic variables we can choose between loading the WP header so we can access WordPress core functions to load custom set options. This would mean extra and most likely unneccesary work for the server because those options are probably already called on the page that loads the stylesheet. A better option (IMO) is to pass the variables in the URL of our dynamic stylesheet so we can access them using PHP&#8217;s $_GET variable.</p><p>If you are manually placing the link to your stylesheet in the head section you should manage to pass your variables quite easily, just add a query string with the variables you&#8217;d like to pass. If you&#8217;re using wp_enqueue_style() to add your stylesheet to the page (which is the correct way) you can pass your variables where you&#8217;re registering your stylesheet, have a look at the following example.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n$color = get_option(''myPlugin_color'', ''111'');\nwp_register_style( ''myPluginStylesheet'', plugins_url("/style.php?color=$color",__FILE__) );\n</pre><h2>Using the custom variables in our PHP stylesheet.</h2><p>Now, you can use the stylesheet just like it was a normal stylesheet and where needed echo or print the variables that have been passed trough the URI. If we want to use the color we passed in our example here as our color for headings we could just do the following.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\nh1,h2,h3,h4{ color: #&lt;?php print $_GET[''color'']; ?&gt;; }\n</pre><p>When looking at the dynamically created stylesheet we would see a normal stylesheet, for instance http://www.yourdomain.com/wp-content/plugins/myPlugin/style.php?color=fff would return the following stylesheet for us.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\nh1,h2,h3,h4{ color:#fff; }\n</pre><h2>The benefits of a CSS stylesheet trough PHP</h2><p>The main reason of why you should use PHP to generate a stylesheet for you with your custom styling rules is the same reason as why you should use an external stylesheet, because it will be cached by the browser. The stylesheet only has to be loaded for new visitors, and is served from the browsers cache when your visitors click trough to other pages of your website. This saves your visitors some bytes (heck, might even be kilobytes) and thus some precious waiting time.</p><p>Of course this example can also be used outside WordPress. The only important thing here is to set the correct content-type header so the browser knows that he&#8217;s (she?) dealing with a CSS file here. There&#8217;s really nothing more to it!</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/327/use-php-to-create-a-css-stylesheet/">Use PHP to create a dynamic CSS stylesheet</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/OUHeMSNXsKU" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:70:"http://dannyvankooten.com/327/use-php-to-create-a-css-stylesheet/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:1:"0";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:65:"http://dannyvankooten.com/327/use-php-to-create-a-css-stylesheet/";}s:7:"summary";s:547:"<p>Did you know that you can create a dynamic CSS stylesheet using PHP? I see a lot of themes and plugins for WordPress where users can set simple styling rules like custom colors. Most of the times these style rules just get printed in the head section of the page where they are needed. Now,<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/327/use-php-to-create-a-css-stylesheet/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/327/use-php-to-create-a-css-stylesheet/">Use PHP to create a dynamic CSS stylesheet</a></p>";s:12:"atom_content";s:3979:"<p>Did you know that you can create a dynamic CSS stylesheet using PHP? I see a lot of themes and plugins for WordPress where users can set simple styling rules like custom colors. Most of the times these style rules just get printed in the head section of the page where they are needed. Now, this could be done a lot easier using a dynamic stylesheet and efficiently using the browser&#8217;s cache, saving your visitors some precious bytes and thus download time.</p><h2>The correct content-type: &#8220;text/css&#8221;</h2><p>To create a dynamic stylesheet using PHP you can just create a file like &#8220;style.php&#8221;. Now, if you call this file from your pages like you would call a normal stylesheet this won&#8217;t