e dynamically created stylesheet we would see a normal stylesheet, for instance http://www.yourdomain.com/wp-content/plugins/myPlugin/style.php?color=fff would return the following stylesheet for us.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\nh1,h2,h3,h4{ color:#fff; }\n</pre><h2>The benefits of a CSS stylesheet trough PHP</h2><p>The main reason of why you should use PHP to generate a stylesheet for you with your custom styling rules is the same reason as why you should use an external stylesheet, because it will be cached by the browser. The stylesheet only has to be loaded for new visitors, and is served from the browsers cache when your visitors click trough to other pages of your website. This saves your visitors some bytes (heck, might even be kilobytes) and thus some precious waiting time.</p><p>Of course this example can also be used outside WordPress. The only important thing here is to set the correct content-type header so the browser knows that he&#8217;s (she?) dealing with a CSS file here. There&#8217;s really nothing more to it!</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/327/use-php-to-create-a-css-stylesheet/">Use PHP to create a dynamic CSS stylesheet</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/OUHeMSNXsKU" height="1" width="1"/>";}i:4;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:61:"Domain move, a new theme and a merry christmas to all of you!";s:4:"link";s:61:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~3/-0S3Vjh0wmE/";s:8:"comments";s:99:"http://dannyvankooten.com/320/domain-move-a-new-theme-and-a-merry-christmas-to-all-of-you/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Fri, 24 Dec 2010 20:22:41 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:16:"Danny van Kooten";}s:8:"category";s:20:"Off-topicDomainTheme";s:4:"guid";s:32:"http://dannyvankooten.com/?p=320";s:11:"description";s:640:"<p>Yesterday I blogged about how long it was since my last post and that it was about time that i&#8217;ve started posting more regularly on Qoate.com. Other things i&#8217;ve mentioned was that I wanted to move from Qoate.com to DannyvanKooten.com so I could start to post under my personal name. And did I mention a<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/320/domain-move-a-new-theme-and-a-merry-christmas-to-all-of-you/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/320/domain-move-a-new-theme-and-a-merry-christmas-to-all-of-you/">Domain move, a new theme and a merry christmas to all of you!</a></p>";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:2519:"<p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/287/back-again-its-been-3-months/">Yesterday I blogged</a> about how long it was since my last post and that it was about time that i&#8217;ve started posting more regularly on Qoate.com. Other things i&#8217;ve mentioned was that I wanted to move from Qoate.com to DannyvanKooten.com so I could start to post under my personal name. And did I mention a new theme? Guess I didn&#8217;t but still, apparently there is one.</p><h3>A new theme and look.</h3><p>To be honest I didn&#8217;t like the old Qoate.com design at all. I am far from a graphic designer but in the past few months i&#8217;ve developed this minimalistic style that I like to use on all my personal sites. I kinda like it, sure, a graphic designer would do way better but this is a tech blog, not the blog some crea bea dude. I&#8217;ve started to use the sidebar more efficiently to display my most recent posts, the recent comments and the most popular posts on DannyvanKooten.com. In the coming weeks there will most likely be some more small changes (read: improvements) on the new theme. Like or dislike this new time or came across a small bug? Please <a href="#respond">let me know</a> trough the comments!</p><h3>Domain move: Qoate.com -> DannyvanKooten.com!</h3><p>I&#8217;ve also taken the time to move everything from Qoate.com to DannyvanKooten.com. Most of the stuff that was available at Qoate.com is already available at this domain and if not, it will be in the next few days. All links that go to Qoate.com get redirected to DannyvanKooten.com now and do show a nice domain move message which I got from Yoast.com, check it out here: <a href="http://yoast.com/change-domain-name/">Change domain and warn your visitors</a>.</p><h3>Merry Christmas!</h3><p>Now, it&#8217;s time to lean back, make some more small improvements and rewrite most of my pages so they are more up-to-date. What could be a better time of the year to do this then christmas? I am heading over to my family now to grab a beer and have a wonderful time, hope you have too! I wish you all a merry christmas and hope to see you in 2011. My good intention for next year is to blog (a lot) more. Your good intention for next year? Visit this blog more often!</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/320/domain-move-a-new-theme-and-a-merry-christmas-to-all-of-you/">Domain move, a new theme and a merry christmas to all of you!</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/-0S3Vjh0wmE" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:95:"http://dannyvankooten.com/320/domain-move-a-new-theme-and-a-merry-christmas-to-all-of-you/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:1:"0";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:90:"http://dannyvankooten.com/320/domain-move-a-new-theme-and-a-merry-christmas-to-all-of-you/";}s:7:"summary";s:640:"<p>Yesterday I blogged about how long it was since my last post and that it was about time that i&#8217;ve started posting more regularly on Qoate.com. Other things i&#8217;ve mentioned was that I wanted to move from Qoate.com to DannyvanKooten.com so I could start to post under my personal name. And did I mention a<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/320/domain-move-a-new-theme-and-a-merry-christmas-to-all-of-you/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/320/domain-move-a-new-theme-and-a-merry-christmas-to-all-of-you/">Domain move, a new theme and a merry christmas to all of you!</a></p>";s:12:"atom_content";s:2519:"<p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/287/back-again-its-been-3-months/">Yesterday I blogged</a> about how long it was since my last post and that it was about time that i&#8217;ve started posting more regularly on Qoate.com. Other things i&#8217;ve mentioned was that I wanted to move from Qoate.com to DannyvanKooten.com so I could start to post under my personal name. And did I mention a new theme? Guess I didn&#8217;t but still, apparently there is one.</p><h3>A new theme and look.</h3><p>To be honest I didn&#8217;t like the old Qoate.com design at all. I am far from a graphic designer but in the past few months i&#8217;ve developed this minimalistic style that I like to use on all my personal sites. I kinda like it, sure, a graphic designer would do way better but this is a tech blog, not the blog some crea bea dude. I&#8217;ve started to use the sidebar more efficiently to display my most recent posts, the recent comments and the most popular posts on DannyvanKooten.com. In the coming weeks there will most likely be some more small changes (read: improvements) on the new theme. Like or dislike this new time or came across a small bug? Please <a href="#respond">let me know</a> trough the comments!</p><h3>Domain move: Qoate.com -> DannyvanKooten.com!</h3><p>I&#8217;ve also taken the time to move everything from Qoate.com to DannyvanKooten.com. Most of the stuff that was available at Qoate.com is already available at this domain and if not, it will be in the next few days. All links that go to Qoate.com get redirected to DannyvanKooten.com now and do show a nice domain move message which I got from Yoast.com, check it out here: <a href="http://yoast.com/change-domain-name/">Change domain and warn your visitors</a>.</p><h3>Merry Christmas!</h3><p>Now, it&#8217;s time to lean back, make some more small improvements and rewrite most of my pages so they are more up-to-date. What could be a better time of the year to do this then christmas? I am heading over to my family now to grab a beer and have a wonderful time, hope you have too! I wish you all a merry christmas and hope to see you in 2011. My good intention for next year is to blog (a lot) more. Your good intention for next year? Visit this blog more often!</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/320/domain-move-a-new-theme-and-a-merry-christmas-to-all-of-you/">Domain move, a new theme and a merry christmas to all of you!</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/-0S3Vjh0wmE" height="1" width="1"/>";}i:5;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:34:"Back again.. it’s been 3 months!";s:4:"link";s:61:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~3/AMnpdF2bFRI/";s:8:"comments";s:68:"http://dannyvankooten.com/287/back-again-its-been-3-months/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Thu, 23 Dec 2010 16:09:03 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:16:"Danny van Kooten";}s:8:"category";s:38:"Off-topicbusycodeigniterPluginssmartje";s:4:"guid";s:32:"http://dannyvankooten.com/?p=287";s:11:"description";s:560:"<p>It&#8217;s been a while since i&#8217;ve posted on Qoate.com due to very busy times at school and at work. Took on a lot of projects, both WordPress and non-WordPress. Due to those busy times i&#8217;ve been unable to update my WordPress plugins while the emails asking for support just kept on rolling in &#8211; sigh.<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/287/back-again-its-been-3-months/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/287/back-again-its-been-3-months/">Back again.. it&#8217;s been 3 months!</a></p>";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:3406:"<p>It&#8217;s been a while since i&#8217;ve posted on Qoate.com due to very busy times at school and at work. Took on a lot of projects, both WordPress and non-WordPress. Due to those busy times i&#8217;ve been unable to update my WordPress plugins while the emails asking for support just kept on rolling in &#8211; sigh. The number of visitors of Qoate.com didn&#8217;t seem to suffer that much too, just a slight decrease over the past 3 months. That slight decrease is a big enough reason to get back to work though!</p><h3>So, what&#8217;s coming?</h3><p>I&#8217;ve planned some free time for the coming months to take on some personal projects. This means I won&#8217;t accept any new customers besides the regular ones I already worked for in the past. This allows me to launch some projects i&#8217;ve been trying to find some time for in the past few months.</p><h3>Recoding my WordPress plugins / offering more support</h3><p>One of thethings i&#8217;d like to do is recode most of my plugins. I think I learned a lot in the past few months, enough to do a better job at  coding those plugins then I did back then. My <a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/wordpress-plugins/newsletter-sign-up/">WordPress newsletter plugin </a> is reaching 5.000 downloads, a number which should be much higher but isn&#8217;t because of me not updating the damn thing or offering any support. That&#8217;s one thing that &#8216;ll change for sure.</p><h3>A new name: Smartje.net</h3><p>Another thing is, i&#8217;m going to release my plugins and blog posts under a different name and on a different domain: <a href="http://DannyvanKooten.com">DannyvanKooten.com</a>. This is because no-one actually knows how to spell &#8220;Qoate&#8221; (besides me). I did make it a valid Google search in the past months though, atleast one thing i&#8217;ve accomplished. I also catch a few people searching for the term &#8220;Qoate&#8221; in Google Analytics so i&#8217;ve taken some baby steps to establishing a name in the WordPress plugin industry. Once this blog has been moved I&#8217;m able to release plugins for WordPress under my personal name, which is a good think cause it builds my name as a brand. :-)</p><h3>CodeIgniter added to my area of knowledge</h3><p>I&#8217;ve worked on quite a few projects like a custom CMS in the past 3 months. This allowed me to explore CodeIgniter a bit, and I must say I like it, a lot! As soon as I moved this blog to Smartje.net and recoded my WordPress plugins I plan on posting some posts on the CodeIgniter topic.</p><p>Well, enough words. As you can see i&#8217;ve got some work to do. I&#8217;m starting right away so please post your comments to keep me motivated!</p><p>On a sidenote: some of you might notice the little Google ad block below. That&#8217;s just me trying to monetize this blog a little. I&#8217;m getting some decent amounts of traffic on this blog and sacrificing a lot of my free time to bake WordPress plugins or posts for YOU guys  (not blaming you though, you didn&#8217;t ask me to ;-)) so why not try to earn a few cents for the effort?</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/donate/">Want to donate? I appreciate! Please do.</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/287/back-again-its-been-3-months/">Back again.. it&#8217;s been 3 months!</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/AMnpdF2bFRI" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:64:"http://dannyvankooten.com/287/back-again-its-been-3-months/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:1:"2";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:59:"http://dannyvankooten.com/287/back-again-its-been-3-months/";}s:7:"summary";s:560:"<p>It&#8217;s been a while since i&#8217;ve posted on Qoate.com due to very busy times at school and at work. Took on a lot of projects, both WordPress and non-WordPress. Due to those busy times i&#8217;ve been unable to update my WordPress plugins while the emails asking for support just kept on rolling in &#8211; sigh.<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/287/back-again-its-been-3-months/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/287/back-again-its-been-3-months/">Back again.. it&#8217;s been 3 months!</a></p>";s:12:"atom_content";s:3406:"<p>It&#8217;s been a while since i&#8217;ve posted on Qoate.com due to very busy times at school and at work. Took on a lot of projects, both WordPress and non-WordPress. Due to those busy times i&#8217;ve been unable to update my WordPress plugins while the emails asking for support just kept on rolling in &#8211; sigh. The number of visitors of Qoate.com didn&#8217;t seem to suffer that much too, just a slight decrease over the past 3 months. That slight decrease is a big enough reason to get back to work though!</p><h3>So, what&#8217;s coming?</h3><p>I&#8217;ve planned some free time for the coming months to take on some personal projects. This means I won&#8217;t accept any new customers besides the regular ones I already worked for in the past. This allows me to launch some projects i&#8217;ve been trying to find some time for in the past few months.</p><h3>Recoding my WordPress plugins / offering more support</h3><p>One of thethings i&#8217;d like to do is recode most of my plugins. I think I learned a lot in the past few months, enough to do a better job at  coding those plugins then I did back then. My <a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/wordpress-plugins/newsletter-sign-up/">WordPress newsletter plugin </a> is reaching 5.000 downloads, a number which should be much higher but isn&#8217;t because of me not updating the damn thing or offering any support. That&#8217;s one thing that &#8216;ll change for sure.</p><h3>A new name: Smartje.net</h3><p>Another thing is, i&#8217;m going to release my plugins and blog posts under a different name and on a different domain: <a href="http://DannyvanKooten.com">DannyvanKooten.com</a>. This is because no-one actually knows how to spell &#8220;Qoate&#8221; (besides me). I did make it a valid Google search in the past months though, atleast one thing i&#8217;ve accomplished. I also catch a few people searching for the term &#8220;Qoate&#8221; in Google Analytics so i&#8217;ve taken some baby steps to establishing a name in the WordPress plugin industry. Once this blog has been moved I&#8217;m able to release plugins for WordPress under my personal name, which is a good think cause it builds my name as a brand. :-)</p><h3>CodeIgniter added to my area of knowledge</h3><p>I&#8217;ve worked on quite a few projects like a custom CMS in the past 3 months. This allowed me to explore CodeIgniter a bit, and I must say I like it, a lot! As soon as I moved this blog to Smartje.net and recoded my WordPress plugins I plan on posting some posts on the CodeIgniter topic.</p><p>Well, enough words. As you can see i&#8217;ve got some work to do. I&#8217;m starting right away so please post your comments to keep me motivated!</p><p>On a sidenote: some of you might notice the little Google ad block below. That&#8217;s just me trying to monetize this blog a little. I&#8217;m getting some decent amounts of traffic on this blog and sacrificing a lot of my free time to bake WordPress plugins or posts for YOU guys  (not blaming you though, you didn&#8217;t ask me to ;-)) so why not try to earn a few cents for the effort?</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/donate/">Want to donate? I appreciate! Please do.</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/287/back-again-its-been-3-months/">Back again.. it&#8217;s been 3 months!</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/AMnpdF2bFRI" height="1" width="1"/>";}i:6;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:30:"HTML 5 Video ‘Full-Screen’";s:4:"link";s:61:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~3/bNlMYgf-v_Y/";s:8:"comments";s:64:"http://dannyvankooten.com/278/html-5-video-full-screen/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Mon, 20 Sep 2010 18:35:06 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:16:"Danny van Kooten";}s:8:"category";s:29:"HTML 5jQueryTutorialUsability";s:4:"guid";s:32:"http://dannyvankooten.com/?p=278";s:11:"description";s:538:"<p>A few days ago I was playing around with HTML 5 and it&#8217;s new (popular) video tag! The result in short: I love(d) it! Getting it to work in all the major browsers wasn&#8217;t that hard at all. I didn&#8217;t even use nasty JavaScript hacks for that, just some basic mark-up fallbacks. But.. I missed<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/278/html-5-video-full-screen/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/278/html-5-video-full-screen/">HTML 5 Video &#8216;Full-Screen&#8217;</a></p>";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:5674:"<p>A few days ago I was playing around with HTML 5 and it&#8217;s new (popular) video tag! The result in short: I love(d) it! Getting it to work in all the major browsers wasn&#8217;t that hard at all. I didn&#8217;t even use nasty JavaScript hacks for that, just some basic mark-up fallbacks. But.. I missed a functionality in all the video players: A full-screen mode. Wouldn&#8217;t be that hard to write a &#8216;full-screen&#8217; function using jQuery, would it?</p><p>That&#8217;s why I decided to write a quick and dirty jQuery hack that somewhat gives a full-screen feeling. Or well, you could. I actually used it for a video to increase in size to it&#8217;s original dimensions. Getting it to increase even more (say full-screen) would just be a matter of changing some values in the script.</p><h2>The basic mark-up for the video tag, works cross-browser</h2><p>Let me start with how I set up my video tag to work in all the major browsers. Have a look.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;video controls width="520" height="310" style="cursor:pointer; z-index:99;"&gt;\n	&lt;source src="../video/kerk-woerden.ogv" type="video/ogg"/&gt;\n	&lt;source src="../video/kerk-woerden.mp4" type="video/mp4"/&gt;\n	&lt;object type="video/x-ms-wmv" data="../video/kerk-woerden.wmv" width="520" height="310"&gt;\n		&lt;param name="src" value="../video/kerk-woerden.wmv" /&gt;\n		&lt;param name="controller" value="true" /&gt;\n	&lt;/object&gt;\n&lt;/video&gt;\n</pre><p>The only major drawback of this method is that I had to use 3 different file types, wmv, mp4 and ogg. But hey, it worked out pretty easy and converting wasn&#8217;t the problem. (BTW: I used <a href="http://www.mirovideoconverter.com/">Miro Video Converter</a>, great free tool)</p><p>I added a simple inline style rule to make it more obvious for the visitor that they can click on the video, we&#8217;ll add<br /> some more evidence later on in the script.</p><h2>Adding a double click event.</h2><p>With most video players it&#8217;s obvious that in order to get the video to play in full screen you have to double click it. That&#8217;s why the first thing we&#8217;re going to do is to add a double click event listener.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n$(document).ready(function() {\n	$(''video'').dblclick(function() {\n		//our method to get the video ''full-screen''\n	});\n});\n</pre><h3>Increasing the video size.</h3><p>Now, what we want is the video to increase in size whenever someone double-clicks it. We can simply do this by changing the width and height attribute using jQuery&#8217;s attr function. Because I didn&#8217;t increase the video to full-screen during my play around I thought it would be nice to increase the video&#8217;s size and then center it on the screen.</p><p>To center the video I few lines of code that you can grab to extend your jQuery library, it might come in handy anyway!</p><pre class="qoate-code">\njQuery.fn.center = function () {\n    this.css("position","absolute");\n    this.css("top", ( $(window).height() - this.height() ) / 2+$(window).scrollTop() + "px");\n    this.css("left", ( $(window).width() - this.width() ) / 2+$(window).scrollLeft() + "px");\n    return this;\n}\n</pre><p>Before we can actually center the video using our newly added function we need to get it out of it&#8217;s parent element. For some this might not be necessary, but it&#8217;s better to be safe. Because we want our visitor to be able to restore the video size to it&#8217;s previous size, let&#8217;s store the original parent element in a variable.</p><p>Another thing we can already add is a clone of the original video element, along with it&#8217;s attributes, event listeners etc.. This is because we want to restore the video the way it was.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n$(document).ready(function() {\n	var parent = $(''video'').parent();\n	$(''video'').dblclick(function() {\n		if(!$(this).hasClass(''fs'')) {\n			//video is not in full-screen mode, let''s go there!\n			clone = $(''video'').clone(true);\n\n		} else {\n			//video is in full-screen, let''s restore it\n		}\n	});\n});\n</pre><p>Notice the check for the class &#8216;fs&#8217;. We&#8217;re not actually using that class for styling purposes, just to see if the video is in full-screen modus. Now all that&#8217;s left to do is to call some functions that actually DO stuff, like increasing the video size!</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n$(document).ready(function() {\n	var parent = $(''video'').parent();\n	$(''video'').dblclick(function() {\n		if(!$(this).hasClass(''fs'')) {\n			//video is not in full-screen mode, let''s go there!\n			clone = $(''video'').clone(true);\n			$(this).appendTo(''body'').attr(''width'',''640'').attr(''height'',''480'').center().addClass(''fs'');\n		} else {\n			//video is in full-screen, let''s restore it\n			$(this).remove();\n			clone.appendTo(parent);\n		}\n	});\n});\n</pre><p>That&#8217;s all! Now, whenever someone double-clicks the video the attributes that set the width and height of the video change to the values you provided in this little script. The video also gets centered on the screen, horizontically and vertically! All that&#8217;s left for you is to add a little more css styling so that it actually LOOKS good.</p><p>Want to see this script in action? Check it out LIVE <a href="http://www.vankootenarchitecten.nl/projecten/video-kerk-woerden.php">here</a>. This is the exact script used above, I only extended it with some overlay functionality and an<br /> easy way to escape our &#8216;full-screen&#8217; mode!</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/278/html-5-video-full-screen/">HTML 5 Video &#8216;Full-Screen&#8217;</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/bNlMYgf-v_Y" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:60:"http://dannyvankooten.com/278/html-5-video-full-screen/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:1:"0";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:55:"http://dannyvankooten.com/278/html-5-video-full-screen/";}s:7:"summary";s:538:"<p>A few days ago I was playing around with HTML 5 and it&#8217;s new (popular) video tag! The result in short: I love(d) it! Getting it to work in all the major browsers wasn&#8217;t that hard at all. I didn&#8217;t even use nasty JavaScript hacks for that, just some basic mark-up fallbacks. But.. I missed<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/278/html-5-video-full-screen/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/278/html-5-video-full-screen/">HTML 5 Video &#8216;Full-Screen&#8217;</a></p>";s:12:"atom_content";s:5674:"<p>A few days ago I was playing around with HTML 5 and it&#8217;s new (popular) video tag! The result in short: I love(d) it! Getting it to work in all the major browsers wasn&#8217;t that hard at all. I didn&#8217;t even use nasty JavaScript hacks for that, just some basic mark-up fallbacks. But.. I missed a functionality in all the video players: A full-screen mode. Wouldn&#8217;t be that hard to write a &#8216;full-screen&#8217; function using jQuery, would it?</p><p>That&#8217;s why I decided to write a quick and dirty jQuery hack that somewhat gives a full-screen feeling. Or well, you could. I actually used it for a video to increase in size to it&#8217;s original dimensions. Getting it to increase even more (say full-screen) would just be a matter of changing some values in the script.</p><h2>The basic mark-up for the video tag, works cross-browser</h2><p>Let me start with how I set up my video tag to work in all the major browsers. Have a look.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;video controls width="520" height="310" style="cursor:pointer; z-index:99;"&gt;\n	&lt;source src="../video/kerk-woerden.ogv" type="video/ogg"/&gt;\n	&lt;source src="../video/kerk-woerden.mp4" type="video/mp4"/&gt;\n	&lt;object type="video/x-ms-wmv" data="../video/kerk-woerden.wmv" width="520" height="310"&gt;\n		&lt;param name="src" value="../video/kerk-woerden.wmv" /&gt;\n		&lt;param name="controller" value="true" /&gt;\n	&lt;/object&gt;\n&lt;/video&gt;\n</pre><p>The only major drawback of this method is that I had to use 3 different file types, wmv, mp4 and ogg. But hey, it worked out pretty easy and converting wasn&#8217;t the problem. (BTW: I used <a href="http://www.mirovideoconverter.com/">Miro Video Converter</a>, great free tool)</p><p>I added a simple inline style rule to make it more obvious for the visitor that they can click on the video, we&#8217;ll add<br /> some more evidence later on in the script.</p><h2>Adding a double click event.</h2><p>With most video players it&#8217;s obvious that in order to get the video to play in full screen you have to double click it. That&#8217;s why the first thing we&#8217;re going to do is to add a double click event listener.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n$(document).ready(function() {\n	$(''video'').dblclick(function() {\n		//our method to get the video ''full-screen''\n	});\n});\n</pre><h3>Increasing the video size.</h3><p>Now, what we want is the video to increase in size whenever someone double-clicks it. We can simply do this by changing the width and height attribute using jQuery&#8217;s attr function. Because I didn&#8217;t increase the video to full-screen during my play around I thought it would be nice to increase the video&#8217;s size and then center it on the screen.</p><p>To center the video I few lines of code that you can grab to extend your jQuery library, it might come in handy anyway!</p><pre class="qoate-code">\njQuery.fn.center = function () {\n    this.css("position","absolute");\n    this.css("top", ( $(window).height() - this.height() ) / 2+$(window).scrollTop() + "px");\n    this.css("left", ( $(window).width() - this.width() ) / 2+$(window).scrollLeft() + "px");\n    return this;\n}\n</pre><p>Before we can actually center the video using our newly added function we need to get it out of it&#8217;s parent element. For some this might not be necessary, but it&#8217;s better to be safe. Because we want our visitor to be able to restore the video size to it&#8217;s previous size, let&#8217;s store the original parent element in a variable.</p><p>Another thing we can already add is a clone of the original video element, along with it&#8217;s attributes, event listeners etc.. This is because we want to restore the video the way it was.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n$(document).ready(function() {\n	var parent = $(''video'').parent();\n	$(''video'').dblclick(function() {\n		if(!$(this).hasClass(''fs'')) {\n			//video is not in full-screen mode, let''s go there!\n			clone = $(''video'').clone(true);\n\n		} else {\n			//video is in full-screen, let''s restore it\n		}\n	});\n});\n</pre><p>Notice the check for the class &#8216;fs&#8217;. We&#8217;re not actually using that class for styling purposes, just to see if the video is in full-screen modus. Now all that&#8217;s left to do is to call some functions that actually DO stuff, like increasing the video size!</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n$(document).ready(function() {\n	var parent = $(''video'').parent();\n	$(''video'').dblclick(function() {\n		if(!$(this).hasClass(''fs'')) {\n			//video is not in full-screen mode, let''s go there!\n			clone = $(''video'').clone(true);\n			$(this).appendTo(''body'').attr(''width'',''640'').attr(''height'',''480'').center().addClass(''fs'');\n		} else {\n			//video is in full-screen, let''s restore it\n			$(this).remove();\n			clone.appendTo(parent);\n		}\n	});\n});\n</pre><p>That&#8217;s all! Now, whenever someone double-clicks the video the attributes that set the width and height of the video change to the values you provided in this little script. The video also gets centered on the screen, horizontically and vertically! All that&#8217;s left for you is to add a little more css styling so that it actually LOOKS good.</p><p>Want to see this script in action? Check it out LIVE <a href="http://www.vankootenarchitecten.nl/projecten/video-kerk-woerden.php">here</a>. This is the exact script used above, I only extended it with some overlay functionality and an<br /> easy way to escape our &#8216;full-screen&#8217; mode!</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/278/html-5-video-full-screen/">HTML 5 Video &#8216;Full-Screen&#8217;</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/bNlMYgf-v_Y" height="1" width="1"/>";}i:7;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:52:"Server side form validation, building an error list.";s:4:"link";s:61:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~3/R85uJNeXQoM/";s:8:"comments";s:87:"http://dannyvankooten.com/268/server-side-form-validation-building-error-list/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Tue, 14 Sep 2010 17:42:12 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:16:"Danny van Kooten";}s:8:"category";s:50:"UsabilityWebdevelopmentDatabasePHPSecurityTutorial";s:4:"guid";s:32:"http://dannyvankooten.com/?p=268";s:11:"description";s:631:"<p>If you&#8217;re developing an application or website where users need to provide information that&#8217;s gonna be stored in a database it&#8217;s always a good thing to validate on the server-side before inserting. Sometimes the only thing you want to make sure is that your visitor filled in all the fields, maybe with a few exceptions.<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/268/server-side-form-validation-building-error-list/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/268/server-side-form-validation-building-error-list/">Server side form validation, building an error list.</a></p>";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:5149:"<p>If you&#8217;re developing an application or website where users need to provide information that&#8217;s gonna be stored in a database it&#8217;s always a good thing to validate on the server-side before inserting. Sometimes the only thing you want to make sure is that your visitor filled in all the fields, maybe with a few exceptions. Here is how I do this server-side without hard coding too much.</p><h2>The $_POST function.</h2><p>When using the POST method to send information from a form there is practically no limit on the amount of information sent (default limit is 8 mb). When submitting large forms with a lot of input fields it can be quite a work to validate all those fields on the server side. Well, it&#8217;s a good thing you don&#8217;t have to do it by hand.</p><h3>$_POST behaves like an array</h3><p>What many people don&#8217;t seem to know is that the $_POST function behaves like an array. This makes it possible to loop trough all the elements in the $_POST array and check if they actually contain a certain number of characters.</p><p>When not containing any characters you should provide your visitors with some kind of list to show them what they forgot or where in your form they went wrong. That, along with a link that points the user back to your form trough their browser&#8217;s history should make it pretty clear for them on what to do to make the form validate. This prevents you from inserting empty strings into your database while still providing your visitors with detailed information on where they&#8217;ve gone wrong.</p><h2>Looping trough the $_POST array, building an error list.</h2><p>Let&#8217;s say we&#8217;ve got ourself a form that provides some information about the visitor along with two password fields to make sure the passwords match. We want to make sure that the visitor filled in all the fields except for adress-line-2, that field is optional. Another thing we want to be sure of is that the two given passwords match.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n//looping trough the $_POST array\nforeach($_POST as $key =&gt; $value) {\n	if($key != ''adress-line-2'' &#038;&#038; (!strlen($value) &gt; 0)) {\n			//uh oh, did we find an empty field?\n	}\n}\n</pre><p>The above snippet loops trough all the variables in the $_POST array. Now we want to build some kind of error list when we find a variable that&#8217;s not from the adress-line-2 input field and doesn&#8217;t contain any characters, and thus is an empty string.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n$error = false;\n$error_list = ''&lt;p&gt;Oooops! We found the following errors!&lt;/p&gt;\n			&lt;ul&gt;''; //start building list\nforeach($_POST as $key =&gt; $value) {\n	if($key != ''adress-line-2'' &#038;&#038; (!strlen($value) &gt; 0)) {\n		$error = true;\n		$error_list .= ''&lt;li&gt;You didn''t provide the ''.$key.'' .'' field&lt;/li&gt;'';\n	}\n}\n$error_list .= ''&lt;/ul&gt;'';\n\n//If any errors were found, output error list.\nif($error) echo $error_list;\n</pre><h3>Adding more specific validation</h3><p>We&#8217;ve got ourself a list of fields that were not provided. Now all that&#8217;s left is to check it the two given passwords match. If they do not, we should add an error to our previously built error list. From here things are pretty straight forward and you could extend the validation process as much as you like.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n$error = false;\n$error_list = ''&lt;p&gt;Oooops! We found the following errors!&lt;/p&gt;\n			&lt;ul&gt;''; //start building list\nforeach($_POST as $key =&gt; $value) {\n	if($key != ''adress-line-2'' &#038;&#038; (!strlen($value) &gt; 0)) {\n		$error = true;\n		$error_list .= ''&lt;li&gt;You didn''t provide the ''.$key.'' .'' field&lt;/li&gt;'';\n	}\n}\n\n// check if the two given passwords match\nif($_POST[''password1''] != $_POST[''password2'']) $error_list .= ''&lt;li&gt;The given passwords do not match!&lt;/li&gt;'';\n\n$error_list .= ''&lt;/ul&gt;'';\n\n//adding a link back to your form\n$error_list .= ''&lt;a href="javascript:history.go(-1);"&gt;&raquo; back to the form&lt;/a&gt;'';\n\n//If any errors were found, output error list.\nif($error) echo $error_list;\n</pre><p>From here you could go on and validate as much as you like. As long as you keep updating your error list it should be pretty clear for your visitors where they did go wrong. Notice the link I added for an easy way back to your form. This ensures the visitor doesn&#8217;t have to fill in all the fields again.</p><p>By the way: If you&#8217;re interested in validation your forms on the cliënt side too, you should definetly have a look on the <a href="http://plugins.jquery.com/project/validate">jQuery validate plugin</a> developed by Jörn Zaefferer. It&#8217;s pretty extended and has some handy conditionals like default formats (date, e-mail, digits, creditcard), minimum and maximum lengths and more.</p><p>Have a better idea on how to handle server-side form validation? Please, let me know!</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/268/server-side-form-validation-building-error-list/">Server side form validation, building an error list.</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/R85uJNeXQoM" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:83:"http://dannyvankooten.com/268/server-side-form-validation-building-error-list/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:1:"0";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:78:"http://dannyvankooten.com/268/server-side-form-validation-building-error-list/";}s:7:"summary";s:631:"<p>If you&#8217;re developing an application or website where users need to provide information that&#8217;s gonna be stored in a database it&#8217;s always a good thing to validate on the server-side before inserting. Sometimes the only thing you want to make sure is that your visitor filled in all the fields, maybe with a few exceptions.<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/268/server-side-form-validation-building-error-list/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/268/server-side-form-validation-building-error-list/">Server side form validation, building an error list.</a></p>";s:12:"atom_content";s:5149:"<p>If you&#8217;re developing an application or website where users need to provide information that&#8217;s gonna be stored in a database it&#8217;s always a good thing to validate on the server-side before inserting. Sometimes the only thing you want to make sure is that your visitor filled in all the fields, maybe with a few exceptions. Here is how I do this server-side without hard coding too much.</p><h2>The $_POST function.</h2><p>When using the POST method to send information from a form there is practically no limit on the amount of information sent (default limit is 8 mb). When submitting large forms with a lot of input fields it can be quite a work to validate all those fields on the server side. Well, it&#8217;s a good thing you don&#8217;t have to do it by hand.</p><h3>$_POST behaves like an array</h3><p>What many people don&#8217;t seem to know is that the $_POST function behaves like an array. This makes it possible to loop trough all the elements in the $_POST array and check if they actually contain a certain number of characters.</p><p>When not containing any characters you should provide your visitors with some kind of list to show them what they forgot or where in your form they went wrong. That, along with a link that points the user back to your form trough their browser&#8217;s history should make it pretty clear for them on what to do to make the form validate. This prevents you from inserting empty strings into your database while still providing your visitors with detailed information on where they&#8217;ve gone wrong.</p><h2>Looping trough the $_POST array, building an error list.</h2><p>Let&#8217;s say we&#8217;ve got ourself a form that provides some information about the visitor along with two password fields to make sure the passwords match. We want to make sure that the visitor filled in all the fields except for adress-line-2, that field is optional. Another thing we want to be sure of is that the two given passwords match.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n//looping trough the $_POST array\nforeach($_POST as $key =&gt; $value) {\n	if($key != ''adress-line-2'' &#038;&#038; (!strlen($value) &gt; 0)) {\n			//uh oh, did we find an empty field?\n	}\n}\n</pre><p>The above snippet loops trough all the variables in the $_POST array. Now we want to build some kind of error list when we find a variable that&#8217;s not from the adress-line-2 input field and doesn&#8217;t contain any characters, and thus is an empty string.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n$error = false;\n$error_list = ''&lt;p&gt;Oooops! We found the following errors!&lt;/p&gt;\n			&lt;ul&gt;''; //start building list\nforeach($_POST as $key =&gt; $value) {\n	if($key != ''adress-line-2'' &#038;&#038; (!strlen($value) &gt; 0)) {\n		$error = true;\n		$error_list .= ''&lt;li&gt;You didn''t provide the ''.$key.'' .'' field&lt;/li&gt;'';\n	}\n}\n$error_list .= ''&lt;/ul&gt;'';\n\n//If any errors were found, output error list.\nif($error) echo $error_list;\n</pre><h3>Adding more specific validation</h3><p>We&#8217;ve got ourself a list of fields that were not provided. Now all that&#8217;s left is to check it the two given passwords match. If they do not, we should add an error to our previously built error list. From here things are pretty straight forward and you could extend the validation process as much as you like.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n$error = false;\n$error_list = ''&lt;p&gt;Oooops! We found the following errors!&lt;/p&gt;\n			&lt;ul&gt;''; //start building list\nforeach($_POST as $key =&gt; $value) {\n	if($key != ''adress-line-2'' &#038;&#038; (!strlen($value) &gt; 0)) {\n		$error = true;\n		$error_list .= ''&lt;li&gt;You didn''t provide the ''.$key.'' .'' field&lt;/li&gt;'';\n	}\n}\n\n// check if the two given passwords match\nif($_POST[''password1''] != $_POST[''password2'']) $error_list .= ''&lt;li&gt;The given passwords do not match!&lt;/li&gt;'';\n\n$error_list .= ''&lt;/ul&gt;'';\n\n//adding a link back to your form\n$error_list .= ''&lt;a href="javascript:history.go(-1);"&gt;&raquo; back to the form&lt;/a&gt;'';\n\n//If any errors were found, output error list.\nif($error) echo $error_list;\n</pre><p>From here you could go on and validate as much as you like. As long as you keep updating your error list it should be pretty clear for your visitors where they did go wrong. Notice the link I added for an easy way back to your form. This ensures the visitor doesn&#8217;t have to fill in all the fields again.</p><p>By the way: If you&#8217;re interested in validation your forms on the cliënt side too, you should definetly have a look on the <a href="http://plugins.jquery.com/project/validate">jQuery validate plugin</a> developed by Jörn Zaefferer. It&#8217;s pretty extended and has some handy conditionals like default formats (date, e-mail, digits, creditcard), minimum and maximum lengths and more.</p><p>Have a better idea on how to handle server-side form validation? Please, let me know!</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/268/server-side-form-validation-building-error-list/">Server side form validation, building an error list.</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/R85uJNeXQoM" height="1" width="1"/>";}i:8;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:59:"jQuery drag and drop inventory (database interaction) [2/2]";s:4:"link";s:61:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~3/ZQgFDFiEDvE/";s:8:"comments";s:94:"http://dannyvankooten.com/259/jquery-drag-and-drop-inventory-database-interaction-22/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Sun, 12 Sep 2010 19:43:36 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:16:"Danny van Kooten";}s:8:"category";s:32:"jQueryPBBGTutorialWebdevelopment";s:4:"guid";s:32:"http://dannyvankooten.com/?p=259";s:11:"description";s:617:"<p>Guess it&#8217;s about time I posted the 2nd part of my jQuery drag and drop inventory tutorial. Well, here it is. In the first part of this tutorial we&#8217;ve created the ability to drag certain items to certain spots, and limit some of these items to a spot. In this part of the tutorial we&#8217;re<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/259/jquery-drag-and-drop-inventory-database-interaction-22/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/259/jquery-drag-and-drop-inventory-database-interaction-22/">jQuery drag and drop inventory (database interaction) [2/2]</a></p>";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:10138:"<p>Guess it&#8217;s about time I posted the 2nd part of my <a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/231/create-drag-and-drop-inventory-using-jquery/">jQuery drag and drop inventory tutorial</a>. Well, here it is. In the first part of this tutorial we&#8217;ve created the ability to drag certain items to certain spots, and limit some of these items to a spot.</p><p>In this part of the tutorial we&#8217;re going to add interaction with a database to store the items held in the inventory, and remember their positions. There are dozens of ways to handle something like this but this should give you an idea! I tried to create the database as flexible as possible, so adding new items for example can easily be done.</p><h2>Adding the database</h2><p>To remember the items a certain player has and into which spot the player stored the item we need to add a database and make a call to a script that updates the database everytime something in the inventory has changed.</p><h3>The table structure of our database</h3><p>Let&#8217;s start with how we&#8217;re going to setup our database. For the inventory and the items i&#8217;ve created two tables. One that remembers the items being held in the inventory and another to store the different items that are available in the game, along with some extra information like to what type they belong.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS `inventory` (\n  `player_id` int(11) NOT NULL,\n  `inventory` text NOT NULL,\n  `weapon_spot` text NOT NULL,\n  `helmet_spot` text NOT NULL\n) ENGINE=MyISAM DEFAULT CHARSET=latin1;\n\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS `items` (\n  `name` text NOT NULL,\n  `type` enum(''weapons'',''helmets'') NOT NULL\n) ENGINE=MyISAM DEFAULT CHARSET=latin1;\n</pre><p>This should all be pretty straightforward. The player id is so we can store the items for different players in our imaginary game. The other 3 columns are for the different items that are in each spot. We&#8217;re going to store the items separated by a comma, but i&#8217;ll get back on that later. The other table is to actually store more information about each item so expanding the items is made easy.</p><h3>Sample database population</h3><p>Now, let&#8217;s add the inventory data for one imaginary player along with the information for each of the 3 items i&#8217;ve also used in part 1 of the tutorial.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\nINSERT INTO `inventory` (`player_id`, `inventory`, `weapon_spot`, `helmet_spot`) VALUES\n(1, ''Dagger'', ''Sword'', ''Helmet'');\n\nINSERT INTO `items` (`name`, `type`) VALUES\n(''Sword'', ''weapons''),\n(''Dagger'', ''weapons''),\n(''Helmet'', ''helmets'');\n</pre><p>The player with the id now has the Dagger in its inventory, the sword in the weapon spot and the helmet in the helmet spot. But, the script and the database are still not connected to eachother. Let&#8217;s get back to the jQuery script for a little while to make a call to our (to be created) database update script.</p><h2>Updating our database</h2><p>Deciding when to update the database can be a little tricky. I&#8217;ve decided to add it to our itemInSpot function, which basically means everytime an item is dropped onto a certain spot the database also gets updated. The thing is, I didn&#8217;t choose to just add the dropped item to it&#8217;s new spot and remove it from it&#8217;s old spot. I&#8217;ve decided to check the position of all the items and send that to our database update script.</p><p>The function I wrote that loops trough all the different items looks something like this.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\nfunction update_spots()\n{\n	// Create a list of all the items\n	var inventory_items = '''';\n	var helmet_spot_item = ($(''#helmet_spot img'').length &gt; 0) ? $(''#helmet_spot img'').attr(''id'') : '''';\n	var weapon_spot_item = ($(''#weapon_spot img'').length &gt; 0) ? $(''#weapon_spot img'').attr(''id'') : '''';\n	$(''#inventory img'').each(\n		function(i) {\n			if($(this).attr(''id'') != '''') {\n				if(inventory_items.length &gt; 1) inventory_items += '','';\n				inventory_items += $(this).attr(''id'');\n			}\n		}\n	);\n	var uri = ''update_inventory.php?helmet_spot=''+helmet_spot_item+''&#038;weapon_spot=''+weapon_spot_item+''&#038;inventory=''+inventory_items;\n	$.ajax({ url: uri });\n}\n</pre><p>This function creates 3 different strings, one for each spot. When there is more then one item in the inventory it seperates the different items by a comma. As you can see we&#8217;re using the ID attribute of our images to get the names of our items. This name has to be exactly the same as the name we&#8217;ve used in our database.</p><p>When we&#8217;ve created the list of items we make an ajax call to update_inventory.php along with the 3 different strings as a GET request. Now all that&#8217;s left is to update the database.</p><h3>The script that updates the database: update_inventory.php</h3><p>If you&#8217;re thinking about creating your own PBBG you&#8217;re probably quite familiar with PHP, so this shouldn&#8217;t be a problem. Let&#8217;s get right to the whole script. Of course if you have any questions, just leave me a comment!</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;?php\nfunction isLegitReq() {\n	return (isset($_SERVER[''HTTP_X_REQUESTED_WITH'']) &#038;&#038; ($_SERVER[''HTTP_X_REQUESTED_WITH''] == ''XMLHttpRequest'')  &#038;&#038; ($_SERVER[''HTTP_HOST''] == $_SERVER[''SERVER_NAME'']));\n}\nif(!isLegitReq()) die(''&lt;!-- silence is golden --&gt;'');\n\n$con = mysql_connect(''DB_HOST'',''DB_USERNAME'',''DB_PASSWORD'') or die(''Could not connect: ''.mysql_error());\nmysql_select_db(''DB_NAME'',$con) or die(''Error selecting DB: ''.mysql_error());\n$helmet_spot=$_GET[''helmet_spot''];\n$inventory_items = $_GET[''inventory''];\n$weapon_spot = $_GET[''weapon_spot''];\n\nmysql_query("UPDATE inventory SET weapon_spot=''$weapon_spot'',helmet_spot=''$helmet_spot'',inventory=''$inventory_items'' WHERE player_id = 1") or die (mysql_error());\n\n?&gt;\n</pre><p>As you can see i&#8217;ve added a little security so hacky player cannot just browse to our update script and give themself some fancy items. The isLegitReq function checks if the request is a valid AJAX-request and comes from the same server as the script is running on.</p><h2>Reading items from the database</h2><p>Almost there! We have a nice database which holds the different items for each spot, but it won&#8217;t actually do anything if we don&#8217;t READ from the database. So, how do we read the different items and put them in the right spots? Take a look at the following snippet of code.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;?php\n$con = mysql_connect(''DB_HOST'',''DB_USERNAME'',''DB_PASSWORD'') or die(''Could not connect: ''.mysql_error());\nmysql_select_db(''DB_NAME'',$con) or die(''Error selecting DB: ''.mysql_error());\n\n$result = mysql_query("SELECT weapon_spot,helmet_spot,inventory FROM inventory WHERE player_id = 1") or die(mysql_error());\n$row = mysql_fetch_array($result);\n\n$inventory_items = $row[''inventory''];\n$helmet_spot = $row[''helmet_spot''];\n$weapon_spot = $row[''weapon_spot''];\n\n//Create a list of all items to decrease MySQL requests.\n$inv_item = explode('','',$inventory_items);\nforeach($inv_item as $tmp_item) {\n	if(strlen($items)&gt;0) $items .= '','';\n	$items .= "''$tmp_item''";\n}\n$items .= (strlen($helmet_spot) &gt; 0) ? ",''$helmet_spot''" : '''';\n$items .= (strlen($weapon_spot) &gt; 0) ? ",''$weapon_spot''" : '''';\n\n// Get all items from the database, create a list with all item names and types\n$query = "SELECT * FROM items WHERE name IN ($items)";\n$result = mysql_query($query) or die(mysql_error().$query);\nwhile($row = mysql_fetch_array($result)) {\n	$item[$row[''name'']] = $row[''type''];\n}\n?&gt;\n</pre><p>So, we&#8217;re reading the items for each of our spots from the database. We put everything in a list and then make another select request to get which type the items belong to. Now we&#8217;ve got ourself some php variables that hold the different items for each spot.</p><h3>Outputting the items for the helmet or weapon spot.</h3><p>If you take a closer look at the above code snippet you&#8217;ll see that we stored the name for the items in the helmet or weapon spot in variables respectively called $weapon_spot or $helmet_spot. Now inside our helmet or weapon div all we have to do is output this variable, this goes as followed.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;?php\n$name = $weapon_spot;\n$type = $item[$weapon_spot];\necho "&lt;img src=\\"$name.png\\" class=\\"$type\\" alt=\\"$name\\" id=\\"$name\\" /&gt;";\n?&gt;\n</pre><h3>Outputting the inventory items</h3><p>Outputting the different inventory items goes somewhat different because we stored these into an array (hence the explode).</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;?php\n	foreach($inv_item as $name) {\n		$type = $item[$name];\n		$output = "&lt;img src=\\"$name.png\\" class=\\"$type\\" alt=\\"$name\\" id=\\"$name\\" /&gt;";\n		if(strlen($output) &gt; 0) echo $output;\n	}\n	?&gt;\n</pre><p>The function that checks for the strlen is just a failsafe cause i&#8217;ve found myself with empty array variables in older versions of PHP. Outputting is pretty basic stuff, it&#8217;s the reading and updating of the database that I considered the somewhat harder parts.</p><h2>The result; a drag and drop inventory that remembers it&#8217;s items and positions</h2><p>If you&#8217;ve followed along and did everything right, good job. I&#8217;m pretty sure I forgot to mention some things I done but i&#8217;m also pretty sure you won&#8217;t do this 100% the same as I did. There are many different ways to handle interacting with the database so feel free to expirement a little, this tutorial should give you a good idea on how to start. If you think we could save ourself a few requests to the database, please share how you would have done it!</p><p>Oh, and before I forget, want to check the result of what we&#8217;ve just made? Check out the demo: <a href="http://www.dannyvankooten.com/demo/inventory-drag-and-drop-with-db/">jQuery inventory with database interaction</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/259/jquery-drag-and-drop-inventory-database-interaction-22/">jQuery drag and drop inventory (database interaction) [2/2]</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/ZQgFDFiEDvE" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:90:"http://dannyvankooten.com/259/jquery-drag-and-drop-inventory-database-interaction-22/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:1:"9";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:85:"http://dannyvankooten.com/259/jquery-drag-and-drop-inventory-database-interaction-22/";}s:7:"summary";s:617:"<p>Guess it&#8217;s about time I posted the 2nd part of my jQuery drag and drop inventory tutorial. Well, here it is. In the first part of this tutorial we&#8217;ve created the ability to drag certain items to certain spots, and limit some of these items to a spot. In this part of the tutorial we&#8217;re<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/259/jquery-drag-and-drop-inventory-database-interaction-22/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/259/jquery-drag-and-drop-inventory-database-interaction-22/">jQuery drag and drop inventory (database interaction) [2/2]</a></p>";s:12:"atom_content";s:10138:"<p>Guess it&#8217;s about time I posted the 2nd part of my <a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/231/create-drag-and-drop-inventory-using-jquery/">jQuery drag and drop inventory tutorial</a>. Well, here it is. In the first part of this tutorial we&#8217;ve created the ability to drag certain items to certain spots, and limit some of these items to a spot.</p><p>In this part of the tutorial we&#8217;re going to add interaction with a database to store the items held in the inventory, and remember their positions. There are dozens of ways to handle something like this but this should give you an idea! I tried to create the database as flexible as possible, so adding new items for example can easily be done.</p><h2>Adding the database</h2><p>To remember the items a certain player has and into which spot the player stored the item we need to add a database and make a call to a script that updates the database everytime something in the inventory has changed.</p><h3>The table structure of our database</h3><p>Let&#8217;s start with how we&#8217;re going to setup our database. For the inventory and the items i&#8217;ve created two tables. One that remembers the items being held in the inventory and another to store the different items that are available in the game, along with some extra information like to what type they belong.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS `inventory` (\n  `player_id` int(11) NOT NULL,\n  `inventory` text NOT NULL,\n  `weapon_spot` text NOT NULL,\n  `helmet_spot` text NOT NULL\n) ENGINE=MyISAM DEFAULT CHARSET=latin1;\n\nCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS `items` (\n  `name` text NOT NULL,\n  `type` enum(''weapons'',''helmets'') NOT NULL\n) ENGINE=MyISAM DEFAULT CHARSET=latin1;\n</pre><p>This should all be pretty straightforward. The player id is so we can store the items for different players in our imaginary game. The other 3 columns are for the different items that are in each spot. We&#8217;re going to store the items separated by a comma, but i&#8217;ll get back on that later. The other table is to actually store more information about each item so expanding the items is made easy.</p><h3>Sample database population</h3><p>Now, let&#8217;s add the inventory data for one imaginary player along with the information for each of the 3 items i&#8217;ve also used in part 1 of the tutorial.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\nINSERT INTO `inventory` (`player_id`, `inventory`, `weapon_spot`, `helmet_spot`) VALUES\n(1, ''Dagger'', ''Sword'', ''Helmet'');\n\nINSERT INTO `items` (`name`, `type`) VALUES\n(''Sword'', ''weapons''),\n(''Dagger'', ''weapons''),\n(''Helmet'', ''helmets'');\n</pre><p>The player with the id now has the Dagger in its inventory, the sword in the weapon spot and the helmet in the helmet spot. But, the script and the database are still not connected to eachother. Let&#8217;s get back to the jQuery script for a little while to make a call to our (to be created) database update script.</p><h2>Updating our database</h2><p>Deciding when to update the database can be a little tricky. I&#8217;ve decided to add it to our itemInSpot function, which basically means everytime an item is dropped onto a certain spot the database also gets updated. The thing is, I didn&#8217;t choose to just add the dropped item to it&#8217;s new spot and remove it from it&#8217;s old spot. I&#8217;ve decided to check the position of all the items and send that to our database update script.</p><p>The function I wrote that loops trough all the different items looks something like this.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\nfunction update_spots()\n{\n	// Create a list of all the items\n	var inventory_items = '''';\n	var helmet_spot_item = ($(''#helmet_spot img'').length &gt; 0) ? $(''#helmet_spot img'').attr(''id'') : '''';\n	var weapon_spot_item = ($(''#weapon_spot img'').length &gt; 0) ? $(''#weapon_spot img'').attr(''id'') : '''';\n	$(''#inventory img'').each(\n		function(i) {\n			if($(this).attr(''id'') != '''') {\n				if(inventory_items.length &gt; 1) inventory_items += '','';\n				inventory_items += $(this).attr(''id'');\n			}\n		}\n	);\n	var uri = ''update_inventory.php?helmet_spot=''+helmet_spot_item+''&#038;weapon_spot=''+weapon_spot_item+''&#038;inventory=''+inventory_items;\n	$.ajax({ url: uri });\n}\n</pre><p>This function creates 3 different strings, one for each spot. When there is more then one item in the inventory it seperates the different items by a comma. As you can see we&#8217;re using the ID attribute of our images to get the names of our items. This name has to be exactly the same as the name we&#8217;ve used in our database.</p><p>When we&#8217;ve created the list of items we make an ajax call to update_inventory.php along with the 3 different strings as a GET request. Now all that&#8217;s left is to update the database.</p><h3>The script that updates the database: update_inventory.php</h3><p>If you&#8217;re thinking about creating your own PBBG you&#8217;re probably quite familiar with PHP, so this shouldn&#8217;t be a problem. Let&#8217;s get right to the whole script. Of course if you have any questions, just leave me a comment!</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;?php\nfunction isLegitReq() {\n	return (isset($_SERVER[''HTTP_X_REQUESTED_WITH'']) &#038;&#038; ($_SERVER[''HTTP_X_REQUESTED_WITH''] == ''XMLHttpRequest'')  &#038;&#038; ($_SERVER[''HTTP_HOST''] == $_SERVER[''SERVER_NAME'']));\n}\nif(!isLegitReq()) die(''&lt;!-- silence is golden --&gt;'');\n\n$con = mysql_connect(''DB_HOST'',''DB_USERNAME'',''DB_PASSWORD'') or die(''Could not connect: ''.mysql_error());\nmysql_select_db(''DB_NAME'',$con) or die(''Error selecting DB: ''.mysql_error());\n$helmet_spot=$_GET[''helmet_spot''];\n$inventory_items = $_GET[''inventory''];\n$weapon_spot = $_GET[''weapon_spot''];\n\nmysql_query("UPDATE inventory SET weapon_spot=''$weapon_spot'',helmet_spot=''$helmet_spot'',inventory=''$inventory_items'' WHERE player_id = 1") or die (mysql_error());\n\n?&gt;\n</pre><p>As you can see i&#8217;ve added a little security so hacky player cannot just browse to our update script and give themself some fancy items. The isLegitReq function checks if the request is a valid AJAX-request and comes from the same server as the script is running on.</p><h2>Reading items from the database</h2><p>Almost there! We have a nice database which holds the different items for each spot, but it won&#8217;t actually do anything if we don&#8217;t READ from the database. So, how do we read the different items and put them in the right spots? Take a look at the following snippet of code.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;?php\n$con = mysql_connect(''DB_HOST'',''DB_USERNAME'',''DB_PASSWORD'') or die(''Could not connect: ''.mysql_error());\nmysql_select_db(''DB_NAME'',$con) or die(''Error selecting DB: ''.mysql_error());\n\n$result = mysql_query("SELECT weapon_spot,helmet_spot,inventory FROM inventory WHERE player_id = 1") or die(mysql_error());\n$row = mysql_fetch_array($result);\n\n$inventory_items = $row[''inventory''];\n$helmet_spot = $row[''helmet_spot''];\n$weapon_spot = $row[''weapon_spot''];\n\n//Create a list of all items to decrease MySQL requests.\n$inv_item = explode('','',$inventory_items);\nforeach($inv_item as $tmp_item) {\n	if(strlen($items)&gt;0) $items .= '','';\n	$items .= "''$tmp_item''";\n}\n$items .= (strlen($helmet_spot) &gt; 0) ? ",''$helmet_spot''" : '''';\n$items .= (strlen($weapon_spot) &gt; 0) ? ",''$weapon_spot''" : '''';\n\n// Get all items from the database, create a list with all item names and types\n$query = "SELECT * FROM items WHERE name IN ($items)";\n$result = mysql_query($query) or die(mysql_error().$query);\nwhile($row = mysql_fetch_array($result)) {\n	$item[$row[''name'']] = $row[''type''];\n}\n?&gt;\n</pre><p>So, we&#8217;re reading the items for each of our spots from the database. We put everything in a list and then make another select request to get which type the items belong to. Now we&#8217;ve got ourself some php variables that hold the different items for each spot.</p><h3>Outputting the items for the helmet or weapon spot.</h3><p>If you take a closer look at the above code snippet you&#8217;ll see that we stored the name for the items in the helmet or weapon spot in variables respectively called $weapon_spot or $helmet_spot. Now inside our helmet or weapon div all we have to do is output this variable, this goes as followed.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;?php\n$name = $weapon_spot;\n$type = $item[$weapon_spot];\necho "&lt;img src=\\"$name.png\\" class=\\"$type\\" alt=\\"$name\\" id=\\"$name\\" /&gt;";\n?&gt;\n</pre><h3>Outputting the inventory items</h3><p>Outputting the different inventory items goes somewhat different because we stored these into an array (hence the explode).</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;?php\n	foreach($inv_item as $name) {\n		$type = $item[$name];\n		$output = "&lt;img src=\\"$name.png\\" class=\\"$type\\" alt=\\"$name\\" id=\\"$name\\" /&gt;";\n		if(strlen($output) &gt; 0) echo $output;\n	}\n	?&gt;\n</pre><p>The function that checks for the strlen is just a failsafe cause i&#8217;ve found myself with empty array variables in older versions of PHP. Outputting is pretty basic stuff, it&#8217;s the reading and updating of the database that I considered the somewhat harder parts.</p><h2>The result; a drag and drop inventory that remembers it&#8217;s items and positions</h2><p>If you&#8217;ve followed along and did everything right, good job. I&#8217;m pretty sure I forgot to mention some things I done but i&#8217;m also pretty sure you won&#8217;t do this 100% the same as I did. There are many different ways to handle interacting with the database so feel free to expirement a little, this tutorial should give you a good idea on how to start. If you think we could save ourself a few requests to the database, please share how you would have done it!</p><p>Oh, and before I forget, want to check the result of what we&#8217;ve just made? Check out the demo: <a href="http://www.dannyvankooten.com/demo/inventory-drag-and-drop-with-db/">jQuery inventory with database interaction</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/259/jquery-drag-and-drop-inventory-database-interaction-22/">jQuery drag and drop inventory (database interaction) [2/2]</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/ZQgFDFiEDvE" height="1" width="1"/>";}i:9;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:45:"Quick WordPress SEO Tip: Appropriate Headings";s:4:"link";s:61:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~3/J0EjZA3Of3M/";s:8:"comments";s:84:"http://dannyvankooten.com/247/quick-wordpress-seo-tip-appropriate-headings/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Thu, 02 Sep 2010 08:11:06 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:16:"Danny van Kooten";}s:8:"category";s:68:"SEOWordPressHeadingsOptimizationSearch Engine OptimizationTutorialWP";s:4:"guid";s:32:"http://dannyvankooten.com/?p=247";s:11:"description";s:581:"<p>Just a quick SEO tip which I feel every theme developer should implement into their themes. It only takes a few minutes and add a little more semantics to your page. Semantics.. When a search engine bot stumbles upon your website it will see your website without any styling. No matter how bold or big<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/247/quick-wordpress-seo-tip-appropriate-headings/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/247/quick-wordpress-seo-tip-appropriate-headings/">Quick WordPress SEO Tip: Appropriate Headings</a></p>";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:3820:"<p>Just a quick SEO tip which I feel every theme developer should implement into their themes. It only takes a few minutes and add a little more semantics to your page.</p><h3>Semantics..</h3><p>When a search engine bot stumbles upon your website it will see your website without any styling. No matter how bold or big your letters are, the spider won&#8217;t look at those words as if they have more importance then other words. You can add meaning/value to certain words by wrapping them inside certain elements. Let&#8217;s say your website contains a grocery list, it makes sense to put those inside a list right?</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;ul&gt;\n        &lt;li&gt;Apples&lt;/li&gt;\n        &lt;li&gt;Peaches&lt;/li&gt;\n        &lt;li&gt;Oranges&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n</pre><p>Now, regarding headings. What is most important on your homepage and what is most important on your post pages? In my opinion on the homepage the thing that&#8217;s most important is your blog&#8217;s title, and on post pages it&#8217;s the post&#8217;s title. So, why not use proper H1 tags to add some more value to your title&#8217;s?</p><p>See where i&#8217;m going to? I want the homepage title to be inside an H1 element on the homepage ONLY. For other pages an H3 element seems appropriate. On those other pages (think posts) the thing that should be wrapped inside the H1 element is the post&#8217;s title!</p><h3>H1 or H3 element?</h3><p>So, every time a page is loaded WordPress should check if the homepage is being viewed. If it is, output the blog&#8217;s title inside an H1 element. If not, use an H3 element. This conditional is actually very simple using WordPress is_home() function, have a look!</p><pre class="qoate-code">\nfunction qoate_heading(){\n	if(is_home()) { $output = ''&lt;h1&gt;''; } else { $output = ''&lt;h3&gt;''; }\n	$output .= get_bloginfo(''name'');\n	if(is_home()) { $output = ''&lt;/h1&gt;''; } else { $output = ''&lt;/h3&gt;''; }\n	echo $output;\n}\n</pre><p>This function will check if the homepage is being viewed, and if so outputs an H1 element. Now add this function to your theme&#8217;s functions.php file! All that&#8217;s left is to replace your current H1 element inside your headers.php with a call to this function.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;h1&gt;&lt;?php bloginfo(''name''); ?&gt; &lt;/h1&gt;\n</pre><p>Becomes&#8230;</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;?php qoate_heading(); ?&gt;\n</pre><p>Now we got our semantics covered for spiders, but what about visitors. They will most likely notice a change in header size. Easy fix here, just add a certain id to your heading inside the function we put in our functions.php file. Use this id to style the heading so both the H1 as the H3 will look the same on all pages.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\nfunction qoate_heading(){\n	if(is_home()) { $output = ''&lt;h1 id="q_heading"&gt;''; } else { $output = ''&lt;h3 id="q_heading"&gt;''; }\n	$output .= get_bloginfo(''name'');\n	if(is_home()) { $output = ''&lt;/h1&gt;''; } else { $output = ''&lt;/h3&gt;''; }\n	echo $output;\n}\n</pre><pre class="qoate-code">\n#q_heading{\nfont-size:20px;\ncolor:black;\n}\n</pre><h3>A little more semantics..</h3><p>You&#8217;ve just added a little more value to the keywords that are important on your blog&#8217;s posts/pages and it only took you 5 minutes! Ain&#8217;t that sweet? Some people argue about the value of H1 headings vs. other words but I am a believer! I&#8217;ve noticed jumps in SERP by just using the appropriate headings on my webpages. It makes no sense using multiple H1 headings on a webpage, right? Semantics are the way to go!</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/247/quick-wordpress-seo-tip-appropriate-headings/">Quick WordPress SEO Tip: Appropriate Headings</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/J0EjZA3Of3M" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:80:"http://dannyvankooten.com/247/quick-wordpress-seo-tip-appropriate-headings/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:1:"0";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:75:"http://dannyvankooten.com/247/quick-wordpress-seo-tip-appropriate-headings/";}s:7:"summary";s:581:"<p>Just a quick SEO tip which I feel every theme developer should implement into their themes. It only takes a few minutes and add a little more semantics to your page. Semantics.. When a search engine bot stumbles upon your website it will see your website without any styling. No matter how bold or big<a class="read_more" href="http://dannyvankooten.com/247/quick-wordpress-seo-tip-appropriate-headings/">Continue reading &#187;</a></p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/247/quick-wordpress-seo-tip-appropriate-headings/">Quick WordPress SEO Tip: Appropriate Headings</a></p>";s:12:"atom_content";s:3820:"<p>Just a quick SEO tip which I feel every theme developer should implement into their themes. It only takes a few minutes and add a little more semantics to your page.</p><h3>Semantics..</h3><p>When a search engine bot stumbles upon your website it will see your website without any styling. No matter how bold or big your letters are, the spider won&#8217;t look at those words as if they have more importance then other words. You can add meaning/value to certain words by wrapping them inside certain elements. Let&#8217;s say your website contains a grocery list, it makes sense to put those inside a list right?</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;ul&gt;\n        &lt;li&gt;Apples&lt;/li&gt;\n        &lt;li&gt;Peaches&lt;/li&gt;\n        &lt;li&gt;Oranges&lt;/li&gt;\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n</pre><p>Now, regarding headings. What is most important on your homepage and what is most important on your post pages? In my opinion on the homepage the thing that&#8217;s most important is your blog&#8217;s title, and on post pages it&#8217;s the post&#8217;s title. So, why not use proper H1 tags to add some more value to your title&#8217;s?</p><p>See where i&#8217;m going to? I want the homepage title to be inside an H1 element on the homepage ONLY. For other pages an H3 element seems appropriate. On those other pages (think posts) the thing that should be wrapped inside the H1 element is the post&#8217;s title!</p><h3>H1 or H3 element?</h3><p>So, every time a page is loaded WordPress should check if the homepage is being viewed. If it is, output the blog&#8217;s title inside an H1 element. If not, use an H3 element. This conditional is actually very simple using WordPress is_home() function, have a look!</p><pre class="qoate-code">\nfunction qoate_heading(){\n	if(is_home()) { $output = ''&lt;h1&gt;''; } else { $output = ''&lt;h3&gt;''; }\n	$output .= get_bloginfo(''name'');\n	if(is_home()) { $output = ''&lt;/h1&gt;''; } else { $output = ''&lt;/h3&gt;''; }\n	echo $output;\n}\n</pre><p>This function will check if the homepage is being viewed, and if so outputs an H1 element. Now add this function to your theme&#8217;s functions.php file! All that&#8217;s left is to replace your current H1 element inside your headers.php with a call to this function.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;h1&gt;&lt;?php bloginfo(''name''); ?&gt; &lt;/h1&gt;\n</pre><p>Becomes&#8230;</p><pre class="qoate-code">\n&lt;?php qoate_heading(); ?&gt;\n</pre><p>Now we got our semantics covered for spiders, but what about visitors. They will most likely notice a change in header size. Easy fix here, just add a certain id to your heading inside the function we put in our functions.php file. Use this id to style the heading so both the H1 as the H3 will look the same on all pages.</p><pre class="qoate-code">\nfunction qoate_heading(){\n	if(is_home()) { $output = ''&lt;h1 id="q_heading"&gt;''; } else { $output = ''&lt;h3 id="q_heading"&gt;''; }\n	$output .= get_bloginfo(''name'');\n	if(is_home()) { $output = ''&lt;/h1&gt;''; } else { $output = ''&lt;/h3&gt;''; }\n	echo $output;\n}\n</pre><pre class="qoate-code">\n#q_heading{\nfont-size:20px;\ncolor:black;\n}\n</pre><h3>A little more semantics..</h3><p>You&#8217;ve just added a little more value to the keywords that are important on your blog&#8217;s posts/pages and it only took you 5 minutes! Ain&#8217;t that sweet? Some people argue about the value of H1 headings vs. other words but I am a believer! I&#8217;ve noticed jumps in SERP by just using the appropriate headings on my webpages. It makes no sense using multiple H1 headings on a webpage, right? Semantics are the way to go!</p><p><a href="http://dannyvankooten.com/247/quick-wordpress-seo-tip-appropriate-headings/">Quick WordPress SEO Tip: Appropriate Headings</a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/dannyvankooten/~4/J0EjZA3Of3M" height="1" width="1"/>";}}s:7:"channel";a:8:{s:5:"title";s:16:"Danny van Kooten";s:4:"link";s:25:"http://dannyvankooten.com";s:11:"description";s:54:"WordPress plugins, PHP blog, jQuery scripts and more..";s:13:"lastbuilddate";s:31:"Wed, 25 May 2011 20:13:34 +0000";s:8:"language";s:2:"en";s:2:"sy";a:2:{s:12:"updateperiod";s:6:"hourly";s:15:"updatefrequency";s:1:"1";}s:9:"generator";s:24:"http://wordpress.org/?v=";s:7:"tagline";s:54:"WordPress plugins, PHP blog, jQuery scripts and more..";}s:9:"textinput";a:0:{}s:5:"image";a:0:{}s:9:"feed_type";s:3:"RSS";s:12:"feed_version";s:3:"2.0";s:5:"stack";a:0:{}s:9:"inchannel";b:0;s:6:"initem";b:0;s:9:"incontent";b:0;s:11:"intextinput";b:0;s:7:"inimage";b:0;s:13:"current_field";s:0:"";s:17:"current_namespace";b:0;s:19:"_CONTENT_CONSTRUCTS";a:6:{i:0;s:7:"content";i:1;s:7:"summary";i:2;s:4:"info";i:3;s:5:"title";i:4;s:7:"tagline";i:5;s:9:"copyright";}s:13:"last_modified";s:29:"Fri, 27 May 2011 19:40:48 GMT";s:4:"etag";s:27:"HxF/jmy2v7rmko8TJ/Kr29LPdac";}', 'no');
